<h2 id="analyzing-data">Analyzing data</h2>

<h3 id="obtaining-weekly-coal-production-data-from-the-eia">Obtaining weekly coal production data from the EIA</h3>

<h3 id="reading-and-cleaning-the-data-in-r">Reading and cleaning the data in R</h3>

<p>I used the <a href="http://xarray.pydata.org/en/stable/">xarray</a> package, which is tailored for handling netCDF files. The information needed for plotting are the coordinates (<strong>Longitude</strong> and <strong>Latitude</strong>) and the data variable <strong>AOD550</strong> (representing aerosol optical depths derived at 550 nm).</p>

<h2 id="plotting-the-aerosol-optical-depth">Plotting the aerosol optical depth</h2>

<p>I used the <a href="https://matplotlib.org/">matplotlib</a> package to create the contour/mesh plot, as well as the <a href="https://scitools.org.uk/cartopy/docs/latest/">cartopy</a> package to change the projection of the map. The cmocean package has color palettes intended for making oceanography/water-related plots, but I liked the <strong>matter</strong> color palette, so I decided to use that for my contour color scale.</p>
